      "content": "Economic models generally indicate that cutting corporate tax rates while simultaneously lowering top marginal income brackets tends to exacerbate long-term wealth inequality. Supporters of these cuts argue that they stimulate investment and job creation, which drives aggregate demand and can lift middle-class wages, thereby narrowing the wealth gap over time. Conversely, most progressive economists contend that since capital and income are increasingly unconcentrated among the wealthy, these combined reductions disproportionately favor high-net-worth individuals and corporations without sufficiently boosting broad-based wages. While behavioral theory suggests some high earners might work more due to higher after-tax returns, empirical evidence from past tax cuts like the 2017 TCJA shows they consistently increase measured inequality by accelerating wealth concentration among the top percentiles.",
